{"title_page": "Skidzyel\u2019", "text_new": "{{Infobox settlement\n|name               = Skidzie\u013a\n|native_name        = \u0421\u043a\u0456\u0434\u0437\u0435\u043b\u044c\n|nickname           = \n|image_skyline      =\n|image_caption      =\n|image_flag         = Flag of Skidal, Belarus.svg\n|image_shield       = Coat of Arms of Skidal, Belarus.svg\n|image_map          = \n|map_caption        = \n|pushpin_map        = Belarus\n|subdivision_type   = [[Countries of the world|Country]]\n|subdivision_name   = {{flag|Belarus}}\n|subdivision_type1  = [[Voblast]]\n|subdivision_name1  = [[Grodno Region]]\n|subdivision_type2  = [[Raion]]\n|subdivision_name2  = [[Hrodna district]]\n|area_magnitude     = \n|area_total_km2         = \n|area_land_km2          = \n|area_water_km2         = \n|population_as_of   = 2009\n|population_note    = \n|population_total   = 10,869\n|population_metro   = \n|population_density_km2 = \n|timezone           = [[Eastern European Time|EET]]\n|utc_offset         = +2\n|timezone_DST       = [[Eastern European Summer Time|EEST]]\n|utc_offset_DST     = +3\n|coordinates        = {{coord|53|35|00|N|24|15|00|E|region:BY|display=inline}}\n|elevation_m        = \n|postal_code_type   = Postal code\n|postal_code        = 231761\n|area_code          = +375 152\n|blank_name         = License plate \n|blank_info         = 4\n|website            =\n|footnotes          = \n}}\n'''Skidzyel''' ({{lang-be|\u0421\u043a\u0456\u0434\u0437\u0435\u043b\u044c|Skidzie\u013a}}, also '''Skidal''', {{lang-be|link=no|\u0421\u043a\u0456\u0434\u0430\u043b\u044c|Skida\u013a}}; {{lang-lt|Skidlius}}; {{lang-pl|Skidel}}; {{lang-ru|\u0421\u043a\u0438\u0434\u0435\u043b\u044c|Skidel}}) is a town in the [[Grodno Region]] of Belarus located 31 kilometers from [[Grodno]].\n\n==History==\nWithin the [[Grand Duchy of Lithuania]], Skidzyel\u2019 was part of [[Trakai Voivodeship]]. In 1795, the town was acquired by the [[Russian Empire]] as a result of the [[Third Partition of Poland]].\n\nFrom 1921 until 1939, Skidzyel\u2019 was part of the [[Second Polish Republic]]. Skidziel is sometimes referred to as a former [[shtetl]] because 80% of its population was Jewish before the [[Holocaust]].  \n\nOn 18 September 1939, in the course of the [[Soviet invasion of Poland]], Skidzyel\u2019 was the site of a pro-Soviet [[communist]] revolt against the Polish government leading to massacre of ethnic Poles by killing squads deployed by delegalized [[Communist Party of Western Belarus]], armed with the smuggled Soviet guns soon before the invasion. The event is referred to by historians as the [[Skidel revolt]].<ref name=\"Wierzbicki-140\">{{cite web | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_BbvQbiaqAEC&lpg=PA140&dq=%22The%20Skidel%22%20revolt&pg=PA140#v=onepage&q=%22The%20Skidel%22%20revolt&f=false | title=Western Belarus in September 1939 \u2013 Polish-Jewish Relations in the ''kresy'' | publisher=Leipziger Universit\u00e4tsverlag | work=Shared History, Divided Memory: Jews and Others in Soviet-occupied Poland, 1939-1941 by Elazar Barkan, Elizabeth A. Cole, Kai Struve | year=2007 | accessdate=December 13, 2012 | author=Marek Wierzbicki, [[Institute of National Remembrance]] | pages=138\u2013140 | isbn=3865832407}}</ref> On 19 September, a unit of the Polish Army restored Polish control in Skidzyel\u2019, but the next day, 20 September, the town was [[Soviet invasion of Poland|occupied by the Red Army]] and, on 14 November 1939, incorporated into the [[Byelorussian Soviet Socialist Republic|Byelorussian SSR]].\n\nFrom 27 June 1941 until 14 July 1944, Skidzyel\u2019 was [[German occupation of Byelorussia during World War II|occupied by Nazi Germany]] and administered as a part of [[Bezirk Bialystok]]. Small shootings of Jews in the forest close to the city were frequent. The ghetto, where they were kept as prisoners, was liquidated on November 2, 1942. The Jews were taken to nearby Kolbassino ({{lang-pl|Kie\u0142basin}}) ''Sammellager'' transit camp to the south, packed with Jews of the [[Grodno Ghetto]].<ref name=\"Yad Vashem\">{{cite web |url=http://www.holocaustresearchproject.org/ghettos/grodno.html |title=The Grodno Ghetto |author=Noah Archer & Chris Webb  |publisher=H.E.A.R.T |year=2007}}; as well as {{cite web |author=[[Yad Vashem]] |title=Lost Jewish Worlds - Grodno, and \"History and Geography of Grodno\" |publisher=The Holocaust Martyrs' and Heroes' Remembrance Authority}}</ref> At this time, they were 22,000 to 28,000 people in the camp. From there, they were sent aboard [[Holocaust trains]] to [[Auschwitz extermination camp]].<ref>[http://yahadmap.org/#village/skidel-grodno-belarus.458 Skidel-Grodno at Yahadmap.org]</ref>\n\nAfter World War II, the Grodno headquarters of the [[Communist Party of the Soviet Union]] was located in Skidal until the collapse of the [[Soviet Union]] in 1991.\n\n<gallery caption=\"Points of interest\" widths=\"210px\" heights=\"140px\">\nFile:Skidel_St._Joseph's_Catholic_Church.JPG|St. Joseph's Catholic Church in Skidzyel\nFile:Skidel Church of sacred New martyrs and confessors of Belarus.JPG|Church of New martyrs and Confessors\n</gallery>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}} \n*Marek Wierzbicki, [https://web.archive.org/web/20110716065744/http://kamunikat.fontel.net/www/czasopisy/bzh/07/07art_wierzbicki.htm Powstanie skidelskie 1939 r.], Bia\u0142oruskie Zeszyty Historyczne nr 7, Bia\u0142ystok, 1997\n\n{{Hrodna Voblast}}\n\n{{coord|53|35|10|N|24|15|07|E|source:kolossus-plwiki|display=title}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Skidziel}}\n[[Category:Towns in Belarus]]\n[[Category:Populated places in Grodno Region]]\n[[Category:Trakai Voivodeship]]\n[[Category:Grodnensky Uyezd]]\n[[Category:Bia\u0142ystok Voivodeship (1919\u20131939)]]\n[[Category:Belastok Region]]\n[[Category:Holocaust locations in Belarus]]\n[[Category:Grodno District]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox settlement\n|name               = Skidzie\u013a\n|native_name        = \u0421\u043a\u0456\u0434\u0437\u0435\u043b\u044c\n|nickname           = \n|image_skyline      =\n|image_caption      =\n|image_flag         = Flag of Skidal, Belarus.svg\n|image_shield       = Coat of Arms of Skidal, Belarus.svg\n|image_map          = \n|map_caption        = \n|pushpin_map        = Belarus\n|subdivision_type   = [[Countries of the world|Country]]\n|subdivision_name   = {{flag|Belarus}}\n|subdivision_type1  = [[Voblast]]\n|subdivision_name1  = [[Grodno Region]]\n|subdivision_type2  = [[Raion]]\n|subdivision_name2  = [[Hrodna district]]\n|area_magnitude     = \n|area_total_km2         = \n|area_land_km2          = \n|area_water_km2         = \n|population_as_of   = 2009\n|population_note    = \n|population_total   = 10,869\n|population_metro   = \n|population_density_km2 = \n|timezone           = [[Eastern European Time|EET]]\n|utc_offset         = +2\n|timezone_DST       = [[Eastern European Summer Time|EEST]]\n|utc_offset_DST     = +3\n|coordinates        = {{coord|53|35|00|N|24|15|00|E|region:BY|display=inline}}\n|elevation_m        = \n|postal_code_type   = Postal code\n|postal_code        = 231761\n|area_code          = +375 152\n|blank_name         = License plate \n|blank_info         = 4\n|website            =\n|footnotes          = \n}}\n'''Skidzie\u013a''' ({{lang-be|\u0421\u043a\u0456\u0434\u0437\u0435\u043b\u044c}}, also \u0421\u043a\u0456\u0434\u0430\u043b\u044c, ''Skidal\u2019''; {{lang-lt|Skidlius}}; {{lang-pl|Skidel}}; {{lang-ru|\u0421\u043a\u0438\u0434\u0435\u043b\u044c}}) is a town in the [[Grodno Region]] of Belarus located 31 kilometers from [[Grodno]].\n\n==History==\nWithin the [[Grand Duchy of Lithuania]], Skidzyel\u2019 was part of [[Trakai Voivodeship]]. In 1795, the town was acquired by the [[Russian Empire]] as a result of the [[Third Partition of Poland]].\n\nFrom 1921 until 1939, Skidzyel\u2019 was part of the [[Second Polish Republic]]. Skidziel is sometimes referred to as a former [[shtetl]] because 80% of its population was Jewish before the [[Holocaust]].  \n\nOn 18 September 1939, in the course of the [[Soviet invasion of Poland]], Skidzyel\u2019 was the site of a pro-Soviet [[communist]] revolt against the Polish government leading to massacre of ethnic Poles by killing squads deployed by delegalized [[Communist Party of Western Belarus]], armed with the smuggled Soviet guns soon before the invasion. The event is referred to by historians as the [[Skidel revolt]].<ref name=\"Wierzbicki-140\">{{cite web | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_BbvQbiaqAEC&lpg=PA140&dq=%22The%20Skidel%22%20revolt&pg=PA140#v=onepage&q=%22The%20Skidel%22%20revolt&f=false | title=Western Belarus in September 1939 \u2013 Polish-Jewish Relations in the ''kresy'' | publisher=Leipziger Universit\u00e4tsverlag | work=Shared History, Divided Memory: Jews and Others in Soviet-occupied Poland, 1939-1941 by Elazar Barkan, Elizabeth A. Cole, Kai Struve | year=2007 | accessdate=December 13, 2012 | author=Marek Wierzbicki, [[Institute of National Remembrance]] | pages=138\u2013140 | isbn=3865832407}}</ref> On 19 September, a unit of the Polish Army restored Polish control in Skidzyel\u2019, but the next day, 20 September, the town was [[Soviet invasion of Poland|occupied by the Red Army]] and, on 14 November 1939, incorporated into the [[Byelorussian Soviet Socialist Republic|Byelorussian SSR]].\n\nFrom 27 June 1941 until 14 July 1944, Skidzyel\u2019 was [[German occupation of Byelorussia during World War II|occupied by Nazi Germany]] and administered as a part of [[Bezirk Bialystok]]. Small shootings of Jews in the forest close to the city were frequent. The ghetto, where they were kept as prisoners, was liquidated on November 2, 1942. The Jews were taken to nearby Kolbassino ({{lang-pl|Kie\u0142basin}}) ''Sammellager'' transit camp to the south, packed with Jews of the [[Grodno Ghetto]].<ref name=\"Yad Vashem\">{{cite web |url=http://www.holocaustresearchproject.org/ghettos/grodno.html |title=The Grodno Ghetto |author=Noah Archer & Chris Webb  |publisher=H.E.A.R.T |year=2007}}; as well as {{cite web |author=[[Yad Vashem]] |title=Lost Jewish Worlds - Grodno, and \"History and Geography of Grodno\" |publisher=The Holocaust Martyrs' and Heroes' Remembrance Authority}}</ref> At this time, they were 22,000 to 28,000 people in the camp. From there, they were sent aboard [[Holocaust trains]] to [[Auschwitz extermination camp]].<ref>[http://yahadmap.org/#village/skidel-grodno-belarus.458 Skidel-Grodno at Yahadmap.org]</ref>\n\nAfter World War II, the Grodno headquarters of the [[Communist Party of the Soviet Union]] was located in Skidal until the collapse of the [[Soviet Union]] in 1991.\n\n<gallery caption=\"Points of interest\" widths=\"210px\" heights=\"140px\">\nFile:Skidel_St._Joseph's_Catholic_Church.JPG|St. Joseph's Catholic Church in Skidzyel\nFile:Skidel Church of sacred New martyrs and confessors of Belarus.JPG|Church of New martyrs and Confessors\n</gallery>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}} \n*Marek Wierzbicki, [https://web.archive.org/web/20110716065744/http://kamunikat.fontel.net/www/czasopisy/bzh/07/07art_wierzbicki.htm Powstanie skidelskie 1939 r.], Bia\u0142oruskie Zeszyty Historyczne nr 7, Bia\u0142ystok, 1997\n\n{{Hrodna Voblast}}\n\n{{coord|53|35|10|N|24|15|07|E|source:kolossus-plwiki|display=title}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Skidziel}}\n[[Category:Towns in Belarus]]\n[[Category:Populated places in Grodno Region]]\n[[Category:Trakai Voivodeship]]\n[[Category:Grodnensky Uyezd]]\n[[Category:Bia\u0142ystok Voivodeship (1919\u20131939)]]\n[[Category:Belastok Region]]\n[[Category:Holocaust locations in Belarus]]\n[[Category:Grodno District]]\n", "name_user": "SrpskiAnonimac", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Skidzyel%E2%80%99"}
